[{"categories":["CS106L"],"content":"CS106L 课程笔记","date":"2023-01-20","objectID":"/2023/01/lec01_welcome/","series":null,"tags":["Cpp","公开课"],"title":"CS106L: Lec01 Welcome","uri":"/2023/01/lec01_welcome/"},{"categories":["CS106L"],"content":" About CS106L Focus is on code: What makes it good, what powerful and elegant code looks like The real deal: No Stanford libraries, only STL Understand how and why C++ was made ","date":"2023-01-20","objectID":"/2023/01/lec01_welcome/:0:0","series":null,"tags":["Cpp","公开课"],"title":"CS106L: Lec01 Welcome","uri":"/2023/01/lec01_welcome/#about-cs106l"},{"categories":["CS106L"],"content":" C++ History","date":"2023-01-20","objectID":"/2023/01/lec01_welcome/:0:0","series":null,"tags":["Cpp","公开课"],"title":"CS106L: Lec01 Welcome","uri":"/2023/01/lec01_welcome/#c-history"},{"categories":["CS106L"],"content":" AssemblyBenefits Unbelievably simple instructions Extremely fast (when well-written) Complete control over your program Drawbacks A lot of code to do simple tasks Very hard to understand Extremely unportable (hard to make work across all systems) ","date":"2023-01-20","objectID":"/2023/01/lec01_welcome/:1:0","series":null,"tags":["Cpp","公开课"],"title":"CS106L: Lec01 Welcome","uri":"/2023/01/lec01_welcome/#assembly"},{"categories":["CS106L"],"content":" Invention of CC made it easy to write code that was Fast Simple Cross-platform Weakness No objects or classes Diﬃcult to write generic code Tedious when writing large programs ","date":"2023-01-20","objectID":"/2023/01/lec01_welcome/:2:0","series":null,"tags":["Cpp","公开课"],"title":"CS106L: Lec01 Welcome","uri":"/2023/01/lec01_welcome/#invention-of-c"},{"categories":["CS106L"],"content":" Design Philosophy of C++Cpp Core Guidelines Only add features if they solve an actual problem Express ideas and intent directly in code Compartmentalization(区块化) is key Do not waste time or space Enforce safety at compile time whenever possible 注意 C++: Basic Syntax + the STL Standard C++: Basic Syntax + std(standard) library ","date":"2023-01-20","objectID":"/2023/01/lec01_welcome/:3:0","series":null,"tags":["Cpp","公开课"],"title":"CS106L: Lec01 Welcome","uri":"/2023/01/lec01_welcome/#design-philosophy-of-c"},{"categories":["CS106L"],"content":" The STL Tons at of EOL general functionality Built in classes like maps, sets, vectors Accessed through the namespace std:: Extremely powerful and wel-maintained ","date":"2023-01-20","objectID":"/2023/01/lec01_welcome/:4:0","series":null,"tags":["Cpp","公开课"],"title":"CS106L: Lec01 Welcome","uri":"/2023/01/lec01_welcome/#the-stl"},{"categories":["CS106L"],"content":"CS106L 课程笔记","date":"2023-01-20","objectID":"/2023/01/lec02_types_and_structs/","series":null,"tags":["Cpp","公开课"],"title":"CS106L: Lec02 Types and Structs","uri":"/2023/01/lec02_types_and_structs/"},{"categories":["CS106L"],"content":" C++ types and structs","date":"2023-01-20","objectID":"/2023/01/lec02_types_and_structs/:0:0","series":null,"tags":["Cpp","公开课"],"title":"CS106L: Lec02 Types and Structs","uri":"/2023/01/lec02_types_and_structs/#c-types-and-structs"},{"categories":["CS106L"],"content":" C++ Fundamental Types int val = 5; //32 bits char ch = 'F'; //8 bits (usually) float decimalVal1 = 5.0; //32 bits (usually) double decimalVal2 = 5.0; //64 bits (usually) bool bVal = true; //1 bit String type #include \u003cstring\u003e // need `string` library std::string str = \"Sarah\"; // double quotes means string // index into a string and get a character char character = str[1]; // 'a' ","date":"2023-01-20","objectID":"/2023/01/lec02_types_and_structs/:1:0","series":null,"tags":["Cpp","公开课"],"title":"CS106L: Lec02 Types and Structs","uri":"/2023/01/lec02_types_and_structs/#c-fundamental-types"},{"categories":["CS106L"],"content":" Dynamic vs Static typing 注意 C++ is a statically typed language. statically typed: Everything with a name (variables, functions, etc) is given a type before runtime.(C++) dynamically typed: Everything with a name (variables, functions, etc) is given a type at runtime based on the thing’s current value.(Python) Runtime: Period when program is executing commands (after compilation, if compiled). # CRASH during runtime, can’t divide a string def div_3(x): return x / 3 div_3(\"hello\") // Compile error: this code will never run int div_3(int x){ return x / 3; } div_3(\"hello\"); Static typing helps us to prevent errors before our code runs. ","date":"2023-01-20","objectID":"/2023/01/lec02_types_and_structs/:2:0","series":null,"tags":["Cpp","公开课"],"title":"CS106L: Lec02 Types and Structs","uri":"/2023/01/lec02_types_and_structs/#dynamic-vs-static-typing"},{"categories":["CS106L"],"content":" OverloadingDeﬁne two functions with the same name but diﬀerent types. 示例 int half(int x) { std::cout \u003c\u003c \"1\" \u003c\u003c endl; return x / 2; } double half(double x) { cout \u003c\u003c \"2\" \u003c\u003c endl; return x / 2; } ","date":"2023-01-20","objectID":"/2023/01/lec02_types_and_structs/:3:0","series":null,"tags":["Cpp","公开课"],"title":"CS106L: Lec02 Types and Structs","uri":"/2023/01/lec02_types_and_structs/#overloading"},{"categories":["CS106L"],"content":" Structstruct: A group of named variables each with their own type. A way to bundle different types together. struct Student { string name; // these are called fields string state; // separate these by semicolons int age; }; Student s; // don't have to add `struct` key word s.name = \"Sarah\"; s.state = \"CA\"; s.age = 21; // use . to access fields // is the same as ... Student s = {\"Sarah\", \"CA\", 21}; // structured binding -- c++17 feature auto [name, state, age] = s; ","date":"2023-01-20","objectID":"/2023/01/lec02_types_and_structs/:4:0","series":null,"tags":["Cpp","公开课"],"title":"CS106L: Lec02 Types and Structs","uri":"/2023/01/lec02_types_and_structs/#struct"},{"categories":["CS106L"],"content":" Pairstd::pair: An STL built-in struct with two ﬁelds of any type. // The fields in std::pairs are named `first` and `second` // initialize std::pair\u003cint, string\u003e numSuffix{1, \"st\"}; std::cout \u003c\u003c numSuffix.first \u003c\u003c numSuffix.second \u003c\u003c std::endl; // is same as ... std::pair\u003cint, string\u003e numSuffix = std::make_pair(1, \"st\"); // also same as ... std::pair\u003cint, string\u003e numSuffix = {1, \"st\"}; To avoid specifying the types of a pair, use std::make_pair(field1, field2) std::string suffix; int num; std::tie(num, suffix) = std::make_pair(1, \"st\"); std::cout \u003c\u003c num \u003c\u003c \" \" \u003c\u003c suffix \u003c\u003c std::endl; // more efficient way in c++17 auto [a, b] = make_pair(3.4, 5); Use std::tie(arg1, arg2) to accept the pair. ","date":"2023-01-20","objectID":"/2023/01/lec02_types_and_structs/:5:0","series":null,"tags":["Cpp","公开课"],"title":"CS106L: Lec02 Types and Structs","uri":"/2023/01/lec02_types_and_structs/#pair"},{"categories":["CS106L"],"content":" AutoType deduction with auto. auto: Keyword used in lieu of type when declaring a variable, tells the compiler to deduce the type. When to use auto? When you don’t care what the type is (iterators) When its type is clear from context (templates) When you don’t know what the type is (lambdas) Don’t use it unnecessarily for return types like below: auto spliceString(const string\u0026 s); 注意 auto doesn’t mean that the variable doesn’t have a type, it means that the type is deduced by the compiler. ","date":"2023-01-20","objectID":"/2023/01/lec02_types_and_structs/:6:0","series":null,"tags":["Cpp","公开课"],"title":"CS106L: Lec02 Types and Structs","uri":"/2023/01/lec02_types_and_structs/#auto"},{"categories":["CS106L"],"content":"CS106L 课程笔记","date":"2023-01-20","objectID":"/2023/01/lec03_streams/","series":null,"tags":["Cpp","公开课"],"title":"CS106L: Lec03 Streams","uri":"/2023/01/lec03_streams/"},{"categories":["CS106L"],"content":" Stream","date":"2023-01-20","objectID":"/2023/01/lec03_streams/:1:0","series":null,"tags":["Cpp","公开课"],"title":"CS106L: Lec03 Streams","uri":"/2023/01/lec03_streams/#stream"},{"categories":["CS106L"],"content":" Stream AbstractionConvert between string-represented data and the real thing. stream: an abstraction for input/output. Streams convert between data and the string representation of data. ","date":"2023-01-20","objectID":"/2023/01/lec03_streams/:1:1","series":null,"tags":["Cpp","公开课"],"title":"CS106L: Lec03 Streams","uri":"/2023/01/lec03_streams/#stream-abstraction"},{"categories":["CS106L"],"content":" Standard iostreams cin: Standard input stream(buffered) cout: Standard output stream(buffered) cerr: Standard error stream(unbuffered) clog: Standard error stream(buffered) Output Streamsstd::out is an output stream. It has type std::ostream. Can only send data using the \u003c\u003c operator. Converts data of any type into string and sends it to the stream. std::cout is the output stream that goes to the console. 示例 std::cout \u003c\u003c 5 \u003c\u003c std::endl; // converts int value 5 to string \"5\" // send \"5\" to the console output stream Input Streamsstd::cin is an input stream. It has type std::istream. Can only send data using the \u003e\u003e operator. Receives a string from the stream and converts it to data. std::cin is the input stream that gets input from the console. The result of cin \u003e\u003e expression is bool, we can use if (cin » …) to check input. 示例 int x; string str; std::cin \u003e\u003e x \u003e\u003e str; //reads exactly one int then one string from console about std::in Each \u003e\u003e only reads until the next whitespace(tab, space, newline). Everything after the ﬁrst whitespace gets saved(saved in buffer) and used the next time std::cin \u003e\u003e is called. Once an error is detected, the input stream’s fail bit is set, and it will no longer accept input. Types matter Stream stops reading at any whitespace or any invalid character for the type. 警告 Why » with cin is a nightmare? cin reads the entire line into the buffer but extracts whitespace-separated tokens. Trash in the buffer will make cin not prompt the user for input at the right time. When cin fails, all future cin calls fail too. Think of a std::istream as a sequence of characters 示例 int age; double hourlyWage; cout \u003c\u003c \"Please enter your age: \"; cin \u003e\u003e age; cout \u003c\u003c \"Please enter your hourly wage: \"; cin \u003e\u003e hourlyWage; //what happens if first input is 2.17? cout \u003c\u003c \"\\nage: \" \u003c\u003c age \u003c\u003c endl; cout \u003c\u003c \"hourlyWage : \" \u003c\u003c hourlyWage \u003c\u003c endl; // age: 2 // hourlyWage: 0.17 When we first input 2.17, the 2 is read and put into variable age, but the std::istream is still reading(not meet whitespace), and save .17 in buffer, when the second std::cin \u003e\u003e called, write .17 into variable hourlyWage. ","date":"2023-01-20","objectID":"/2023/01/lec03_streams/:1:2","series":null,"tags":["Cpp","公开课"],"title":"CS106L: Lec03 Streams","uri":"/2023/01/lec03_streams/#standard-iostreams"},{"categories":["CS106L"],"content":" Standard iostreams cin: Standard input stream(buffered) cout: Standard output stream(buffered) cerr: Standard error stream(unbuffered) clog: Standard error stream(buffered) Output Streamsstd::out is an output stream. It has type std::ostream. Can only send data using the \u003c\u003c operator. Converts data of any type into string and sends it to the stream. std::cout is the output stream that goes to the console. 示例 std::cout \u003c\u003c 5 \u003c\u003c std::endl; // converts int value 5 to string \"5\" // send \"5\" to the console output stream Input Streamsstd::cin is an input stream. It has type std::istream. Can only send data using the \u003e\u003e operator. Receives a string from the stream and converts it to data. std::cin is the input stream that gets input from the console. The result of cin \u003e\u003e expression is bool, we can use if (cin » …) to check input. 示例 int x; string str; std::cin \u003e\u003e x \u003e\u003e str; //reads exactly one int then one string from console about std::in Each \u003e\u003e only reads until the next whitespace(tab, space, newline). Everything after the ﬁrst whitespace gets saved(saved in buffer) and used the next time std::cin \u003e\u003e is called. Once an error is detected, the input stream’s fail bit is set, and it will no longer accept input. Types matter Stream stops reading at any whitespace or any invalid character for the type. 警告 Why » with cin is a nightmare? cin reads the entire line into the buffer but extracts whitespace-separated tokens. Trash in the buffer will make cin not prompt the user for input at the right time. When cin fails, all future cin calls fail too. Think of a std::istream as a sequence of characters 示例 int age; double hourlyWage; cout \u003c\u003c \"Please enter your age: \"; cin \u003e\u003e age; cout \u003c\u003c \"Please enter your hourly wage: \"; cin \u003e\u003e hourlyWage; //what happens if first input is 2.17? cout \u003c\u003c \"\\nage: \" \u003c\u003c age \u003c\u003c endl; cout \u003c\u003c \"hourlyWage : \" \u003c\u003c hourlyWage \u003c\u003c endl; // age: 2 // hourlyWage: 0.17 When we first input 2.17, the 2 is read and put into variable age, but the std::istream is still reading(not meet whitespace), and save .17 in buffer, when the second std::cin \u003e\u003e called, write .17 into variable hourlyWage. ","date":"2023-01-20","objectID":"/2023/01/lec03_streams/:1:2","series":null,"tags":["Cpp","公开课"],"title":"CS106L: Lec03 Streams","uri":"/2023/01/lec03_streams/#output-streams"},{"categories":["CS106L"],"content":" Standard iostreams cin: Standard input stream(buffered) cout: Standard output stream(buffered) cerr: Standard error stream(unbuffered) clog: Standard error stream(buffered) Output Streamsstd::out is an output stream. It has type std::ostream. Can only send data using the \u003c\u003c operator. Converts data of any type into string and sends it to the stream. std::cout is the output stream that goes to the console. 示例 std::cout \u003c\u003c 5 \u003c\u003c std::endl; // converts int value 5 to string \"5\" // send \"5\" to the console output stream Input Streamsstd::cin is an input stream. It has type std::istream. Can only send data using the \u003e\u003e operator. Receives a string from the stream and converts it to data. std::cin is the input stream that gets input from the console. The result of cin \u003e\u003e expression is bool, we can use if (cin » …) to check input. 示例 int x; string str; std::cin \u003e\u003e x \u003e\u003e str; //reads exactly one int then one string from console about std::in Each \u003e\u003e only reads until the next whitespace(tab, space, newline). Everything after the ﬁrst whitespace gets saved(saved in buffer) and used the next time std::cin \u003e\u003e is called. Once an error is detected, the input stream’s fail bit is set, and it will no longer accept input. Types matter Stream stops reading at any whitespace or any invalid character for the type. 警告 Why » with cin is a nightmare? cin reads the entire line into the buffer but extracts whitespace-separated tokens. Trash in the buffer will make cin not prompt the user for input at the right time. When cin fails, all future cin calls fail too. Think of a std::istream as a sequence of characters 示例 int age; double hourlyWage; cout \u003c\u003c \"Please enter your age: \"; cin \u003e\u003e age; cout \u003c\u003c \"Please enter your hourly wage: \"; cin \u003e\u003e hourlyWage; //what happens if first input is 2.17? cout \u003c\u003c \"\\nage: \" \u003c\u003c age \u003c\u003c endl; cout \u003c\u003c \"hourlyWage : \" \u003c\u003c hourlyWage \u003c\u003c endl; // age: 2 // hourlyWage: 0.17 When we first input 2.17, the 2 is read and put into variable age, but the std::istream is still reading(not meet whitespace), and save .17 in buffer, when the second std::cin \u003e\u003e called, write .17 into variable hourlyWage. ","date":"2023-01-20","objectID":"/2023/01/lec03_streams/:1:2","series":null,"tags":["Cpp","公开课"],"title":"CS106L: Lec03 Streams","uri":"/2023/01/lec03_streams/#input-streams"},{"categories":["CS106L"],"content":" State bitsWe can use state bits to check if the stream has errors. Good bit: ready for read/write Fail bit: previous operation failed, all future operations frozen type mismatch file can’t be opened seekg failed EOF bit: previous operation reached the end of buffer content Bad bit: external error, likely irrecoverable 示例 std::istringstream iss(str); cout \u003c\u003c iss.good() \u003c\u003c endl; cout \u003c\u003c iss.fail() \u003c\u003c endl; cout \u003c\u003c iss.eof() \u003c\u003c endl; cout \u003c\u003c iss.bad() \u003c\u003c endl; ","date":"2023-01-20","objectID":"/2023/01/lec03_streams/:1:3","series":null,"tags":["Cpp","公开课"],"title":"CS106L: Lec03 Streams","uri":"/2023/01/lec03_streams/#state-bits"},{"categories":["CS106L"],"content":" std::getline() Defined in header \u003cstring\u003e Used to read a string or a line from an input stream. Signature: istream\u0026 getline(istream\u0026 is, string\u0026 str, char delim); is: Stream to read from str: Place where input from stream is stored delim: When to stop reading (\\n as default) How it works Clears contents in str Extracts chars from is and stores them in str until: End of ﬁle buffer of is, sets EOF bit (can be checked using is.eof()) Next char in is is delim(default is \\n), extracts but does not store delim str max size is reached, sets FAIL bit (can be checked using is.fail()) 警告 Notice getline(istream\u0026 stream, string\u0026 line) takes in both parameters by reference! How to use std::getline() 示例 string line; std::getline(cin, line); // now line has changed std::cout \u003c\u003c line \u003c\u003c std::endl; Compare \u003e\u003e with geline: \u003e\u003e reads up to the next whitespace character and does not go past that whitespace character. getline reads up to the next delimiter (by default, ‘\\n’), and does go past that delimiter. ","date":"2023-01-20","objectID":"/2023/01/lec03_streams/:1:4","series":null,"tags":["Cpp","公开课"],"title":"CS106L: Lec03 Streams","uri":"/2023/01/lec03_streams/#stdgetline"},{"categories":["CS106L"],"content":" File Streams Output File Streams Defined in header \u003cfstream\u003e Have type std::ofstream Can only send data using the \u003c\u003c operator. Converts data of any type into a string and sends it to the ﬁle stream. Must initialize your own ofstream object linked to your ﬁle. 示例 std::ofstream out_file(\"out.txt\"); // out_file is now an ofstream that outputs to out.txt out_file \u003c\u003c 5 \u003c\u003c std::endl; // out.txt now contains 5 Input File Streams Defined in header \u003cfstream\u003e Have type std::ifstream. Only receives strings using the \u003e\u003e operator. Receives strings from a ﬁle and converts it to data of any type. Must initialize your own ifstream object linked to your ﬁle. 示例 std::ifstream in_file(\"out.txt\"); // in_file is now an ifstream that reads from out.txt string str; string str; in_file \u003e\u003e str; // first word in out.txt goes into str File mode ios::app: append ios::ate: at end ios::in: open file for reading ios::out: open file for writing ios::trunc: truncate, if the file exists, empty the file contents when open the file multi mode we can use | to combine two modes, like ios::out | ios::ate ","date":"2023-01-20","objectID":"/2023/01/lec03_streams/:1:5","series":null,"tags":["Cpp","公开课"],"title":"CS106L: Lec03 Streams","uri":"/2023/01/lec03_streams/#file-streams"},{"categories":["CS106L"],"content":" File Streams Output File Streams Defined in header Have type std::ofstream Can only send data using the \u003c\u003c operator. Converts data of any type into a string and sends it to the ﬁle stream. Must initialize your own ofstream object linked to your ﬁle. 示例 std::ofstream out_file(\"out.txt\"); // out_file is now an ofstream that outputs to out.txt out_file \u003c\u003c 5 \u003c\u003c std::endl; // out.txt now contains 5 Input File Streams Defined in header Have type std::ifstream. Only receives strings using the \u003e\u003e operator. Receives strings from a ﬁle and converts it to data of any type. Must initialize your own ifstream object linked to your ﬁle. 示例 std::ifstream in_file(\"out.txt\"); // in_file is now an ifstream that reads from out.txt string str; string str; in_file \u003e\u003e str; // first word in out.txt goes into str File mode ios::app: append ios::ate: at end ios::in: open file for reading ios::out: open file for writing ios::trunc: truncate, if the file exists, empty the file contents when open the file multi mode we can use | to combine two modes, like ios::out | ios::ate ","date":"2023-01-20","objectID":"/2023/01/lec03_streams/:1:5","series":null,"tags":["Cpp","公开课"],"title":"CS106L: Lec03 Streams","uri":"/2023/01/lec03_streams/#output-file-streams"},{"categories":["CS106L"],"content":" File Streams Output File Streams Defined in header Have type std::ofstream Can only send data using the \u003c\u003c operator. Converts data of any type into a string and sends it to the ﬁle stream. Must initialize your own ofstream object linked to your ﬁle. 示例 std::ofstream out_file(\"out.txt\"); // out_file is now an ofstream that outputs to out.txt out_file \u003c\u003c 5 \u003c\u003c std::endl; // out.txt now contains 5 Input File Streams Defined in header Have type std::ifstream. Only receives strings using the \u003e\u003e operator. Receives strings from a ﬁle and converts it to data of any type. Must initialize your own ifstream object linked to your ﬁle. 示例 std::ifstream in_file(\"out.txt\"); // in_file is now an ifstream that reads from out.txt string str; string str; in_file \u003e\u003e str; // first word in out.txt goes into str File mode ios::app: append ios::ate: at end ios::in: open file for reading ios::out: open file for writing ios::trunc: truncate, if the file exists, empty the file contents when open the file multi mode we can use | to combine two modes, like ios::out | ios::ate ","date":"2023-01-20","objectID":"/2023/01/lec03_streams/:1:5","series":null,"tags":["Cpp","公开课"],"title":"CS106L: Lec03 Streams","uri":"/2023/01/lec03_streams/#input-file-streams"},{"categories":["CS106L"],"content":" File Streams Output File Streams Defined in header Have type std::ofstream Can only send data using the \u003c\u003c operator. Converts data of any type into a string and sends it to the ﬁle stream. Must initialize your own ofstream object linked to your ﬁle. 示例 std::ofstream out_file(\"out.txt\"); // out_file is now an ofstream that outputs to out.txt out_file \u003c\u003c 5 \u003c\u003c std::endl; // out.txt now contains 5 Input File Streams Defined in header Have type std::ifstream. Only receives strings using the \u003e\u003e operator. Receives strings from a ﬁle and converts it to data of any type. Must initialize your own ifstream object linked to your ﬁle. 示例 std::ifstream in_file(\"out.txt\"); // in_file is now an ifstream that reads from out.txt string str; string str; in_file \u003e\u003e str; // first word in out.txt goes into str File mode ios::app: append ios::ate: at end ios::in: open file for reading ios::out: open file for writing ios::trunc: truncate, if the file exists, empty the file contents when open the file multi mode we can use | to combine two modes, like ios::out | ios::ate ","date":"2023-01-20","objectID":"/2023/01/lec03_streams/:1:5","series":null,"tags":["Cpp","公开课"],"title":"CS106L: Lec03 Streams","uri":"/2023/01/lec03_streams/#file-mode"},{"categories":["CS106L"],"content":" String Streams Input stream: std::istringstream Give any data type to the istringstream, it’ll store it as a string. (data type -\u003e string) Output stream: std::ostringstream Make an ostringstream out of a string, read from it word/type by word/type. (string -\u003e data type) 示例 // ostringstream std::ostringstream oss(\"Hello world\"); cout \u003c\u003c oss.str() \u003c\u003c endl; // Hello world oss \u003c\u003c \"Game over\"; cout \u003c\u003c oss.str() \u003c\u003c endl; // Game overld // Q: why? // A: The buffer doesn't refresh. // istringstream Student reverseJudgementCall(string judgement) { // input: “Sarah age 21, rocks” std::istringstream converter(judgement); string fluff; int age; bool lovesCpp; string name; converter \u003e\u003e name; // Sarah converter.ignore() // pass over a character -\u003e age converter \u003e\u003e age; // 21 converter \u003e\u003e fluff; // , string cool; converter \u003e\u003e cool; // rocks if (cool == \"rocks\") return Student{name, age, \"bliss\"}; else return Student{name, age, \"misery\"}; } ","date":"2023-01-20","objectID":"/2023/01/lec03_streams/:1:6","series":null,"tags":["Cpp","公开课"],"title":"CS106L: Lec03 Streams","uri":"/2023/01/lec03_streams/#string-streams"},{"categories":["CS106L"],"content":"CS106L 课程笔记","date":"2023-01-20","objectID":"/2023/01/lec04_init_and_ref/","series":null,"tags":["Cpp","公开课"],"title":"CS106L: Lec04 Initialization and Reference","uri":"/2023/01/lec04_init_and_ref/"},{"categories":["CS106L"],"content":" InitializationInitialization: How we provide initial values to variables. ","date":"2023-01-20","objectID":"/2023/01/lec04_init_and_ref/:1:0","series":null,"tags":["Cpp","公开课"],"title":"CS106L: Lec04 Initialization and Reference","uri":"/2023/01/lec04_init_and_ref/#initialization"},{"categories":["CS106L"],"content":" Uniform initializationInitialization while we declare a variable. Uniform initialization: Curly bracket initialization. Available for all types, immediate initialization on declaration! Use uniform initialization to initialize every ﬁeld of non-primitive typed variables. 示例 Student s{\"Sarah\", \"CA\", 21}; // struct std::pair\u003cint, string\u003e numSuffix{1, \"st\"}; // pair std::vector\u003cint\u003e vec{1, 3, 5}; // vector int x{5}; // int string str{\"Name\"}; //string ","date":"2023-01-20","objectID":"/2023/01/lec04_init_and_ref/:1:1","series":null,"tags":["Cpp","公开课"],"title":"CS106L: Lec04 Initialization and Reference","uri":"/2023/01/lec04_init_and_ref/#uniform-initialization"},{"categories":["CS106L"],"content":" Structured bindingInitialize dierctly from the contens of a struct. 示例 // pair auto p = std::make_pair(\"str\", 5); auto [a, b] = p; // struct Student s{\"Sarah\", 20, \"TA\"}; auto [name, age, staff] = s; ","date":"2023-01-20","objectID":"/2023/01/lec04_init_and_ref/:1:2","series":null,"tags":["Cpp","公开课"],"title":"CS106L: Lec04 Initialization and Reference","uri":"/2023/01/lec04_init_and_ref/#structured-binding"},{"categories":["CS106L"],"content":" ReferencesReferences: An alias(another name) for a named variable. We can only create references to variables. The cpp compiler does not allocate separate memory space for references. References must have initialization. 示例 void change_x(int\u0026 x){ x = 0; // changes to x will persist } void keep_x(int x){ x = 0; } change_x(a); // a becomes a reference to x keep_x(b); // b becomes a copy of x cout \u003c\u003c a \u003c\u003c endl; // 0 cout \u003c\u003c b \u003c\u003c endl; // 100 std::vector\u003cint\u003e original{1, 2}; std::vector\u003cint\u003e copy = original; std::vector\u003cint\u003e\u0026 ref = original; // `=` automatically makes a copy, must use `\u0026` to avoid this ","date":"2023-01-20","objectID":"/2023/01/lec04_init_and_ref/:2:0","series":null,"tags":["Cpp","公开课"],"title":"CS106L: Lec04 Initialization and Reference","uri":"/2023/01/lec04_init_and_ref/#references"},{"categories":["CS106L"],"content":" L-values and R-values L-values L-values can appear on the left or right of an = L-values have names L-values are not temporary L-values live until the end of the scope R-values R-values can only appear on the right of an = R-values don’t have names R-values are temporary R-values live until the end of the line ","date":"2023-01-20","objectID":"/2023/01/lec04_init_and_ref/:2:1","series":null,"tags":["Cpp","公开课"],"title":"CS106L: Lec04 Initialization and Reference","uri":"/2023/01/lec04_init_and_ref/#l-values-and-r-values"},{"categories":["CS106L"],"content":" L-values and R-values L-values L-values can appear on the left or right of an = L-values have names L-values are not temporary L-values live until the end of the scope R-values R-values can only appear on the right of an = R-values don’t have names R-values are temporary R-values live until the end of the line ","date":"2023-01-20","objectID":"/2023/01/lec04_init_and_ref/:2:1","series":null,"tags":["Cpp","公开课"],"title":"CS106L: Lec04 Initialization and Reference","uri":"/2023/01/lec04_init_and_ref/#l-values"},{"categories":["CS106L"],"content":" L-values and R-values L-values L-values can appear on the left or right of an = L-values have names L-values are not temporary L-values live until the end of the scope R-values R-values can only appear on the right of an = R-values don’t have names R-values are temporary R-values live until the end of the line ","date":"2023-01-20","objectID":"/2023/01/lec04_init_and_ref/:2:1","series":null,"tags":["Cpp","公开课"],"title":"CS106L: Lec04 Initialization and Reference","uri":"/2023/01/lec04_init_and_ref/#r-values"},{"categories":["CS106L"],"content":" Constconst: keyword indicating a variable, function or parameter can’t be modiﬁed. 示例 std::vector\u003cint\u003e vec{1, 2, 3}; const std::vector\u003cint\u003e c_vec{7, 8}; // a const variable std::vector\u003cint\u003e\u0026 ref = vec; // a regular reference const std::vector\u003cint\u003e\u0026 c_ref = vec; // a const reference vec.push_back(3); // OK c_vec.push_back(3); // BAD - const ref.push_back(3); // OK c_ref.push_back(3); // BAD - const ","date":"2023-01-20","objectID":"/2023/01/lec04_init_and_ref/:3:0","series":null,"tags":["Cpp","公开课"],"title":"CS106L: Lec04 Initialization and Reference","uri":"/2023/01/lec04_init_and_ref/#const"},{"categories":["CS106L"],"content":" Const ReferencesCan’t declare non-const reference to const variable. 示例 const std::vector\u003cint\u003e c_vec{7, 8}; // a const variable std::vector\u003cint\u003e\u0026 bad_ref = c_vec; // BAD const std::vector\u003cint\u003e\u0026 good_ref = c_vec; // Fixed When do we use references/const references If we’re working with a variable that takes up little space in memory (e.g. int, double), we don’t need to use a reference and can just copy the variable. If we need to alias the variable to modify it(e.g. in a function), we can use references. If we don’t need to modify the variable, but it’s a big variable (e.g. std::vector), we can use const references. We can return references as well, but note that the parameter must be a non-const reference to return. 示例 int\u0026 front(std::vector\u003cint\u003e \u0026 vec){ return vec[0]; } int main(void){ std::vector\u003cint\u003e nums{1, 2, 3}; front(nums) = 4; // vec = {4, 2, 3} return 0; } R-values can be bound to const reference. 示例 int foo(const int \u0026a){ return a + 3; } int main(void){ foo(1 + 2); // `1+2` is a r-value, but can be passed in // as const reference. } ","date":"2023-01-20","objectID":"/2023/01/lec04_init_and_ref/:3:1","series":null,"tags":["Cpp","公开课"],"title":"CS106L: Lec04 Initialization and Reference","uri":"/2023/01/lec04_init_and_ref/#const-references"},{"categories":["CS106L"],"content":" Const pointersConst pointer means this pointer is unchangeable, but what the pointer points to is changeable. 示例 using iterator = std::string*; using const_iterator = const std::string*; // string * const, const ptr to non-const obj const iterator it_c = str.begin(); // ok! it_c is a const pointer to non-const object *it_c = \"hi\" ; //not ok! can’t change where a const pointer points it_c++; // const string*, a non-const ptr to const obj const_iterator c_it = str.begin(); // totally ok! the pointer itself is non-const c_it++; // not ok! can’t change underlying const object *c_it = \"hi\"; // allowed! can always read a const object, just can't change cout \u003c\u003c *c_it \u003c\u003c endl; ","date":"2023-01-20","objectID":"/2023/01/lec04_init_and_ref/:3:2","series":null,"tags":["Cpp","公开课"],"title":"CS106L: Lec04 Initialization and Reference","uri":"/2023/01/lec04_init_and_ref/#const-pointers"},{"categories":["CS106L"],"content":" Const functionsconst-interface: All member functions marked const in a class deﬁnition. Objects of type const ClassName may only use the const-interface. Can’t call a non-const function in a const function. Every member function of a class that doesn’t change its member variables should be marked const. 示例 class Str { public: size_t size() const; bool empty() const; const std::string\u0026 at(size_t index) const; ... } ","date":"2023-01-20","objectID":"/2023/01/lec04_init_and_ref/:3:3","series":null,"tags":["Cpp","公开课"],"title":"CS106L: Lec04 Initialization and Reference","uri":"/2023/01/lec04_init_and_ref/#const-functions"},{"categories":["CS106L"],"content":" Parameter passing rulesBasic parameter passing rules Advanced parameter passing rules ","date":"2023-01-20","objectID":"/2023/01/lec04_init_and_ref/:3:4","series":null,"tags":["Cpp","公开课"],"title":"CS106L: Lec04 Initialization and Reference","uri":"/2023/01/lec04_init_and_ref/#parameter-passing-rules"},{"categories":["CS106L"],"content":"CS106L 课程笔记","date":"2023-01-20","objectID":"/2023/01/lec05_containers/","series":null,"tags":["Cpp","公开课"],"title":"CS106L: Lec05 Containers","uri":"/2023/01/lec05_containers/"},{"categories":["CS106L"],"content":" STLStandard template library includes Algorithms Functors/Lambdas Inerators Containers Adaptors ","date":"2023-01-20","objectID":"/2023/01/lec05_containers/:1:0","series":null,"tags":["Cpp","公开课"],"title":"CS106L: Lec05 Containers","uri":"/2023/01/lec05_containers/#stl"},{"categories":["CS106L"],"content":" ContainerContainer: An object that allows us to collect other objects together and interact with them in some way. Organization: Related data can be packaged together. Standardization: Common features are expected and implemented. Abstraction: Complex ideas made easier to utilize by clients. ","date":"2023-01-20","objectID":"/2023/01/lec05_containers/:2:0","series":null,"tags":["Cpp","公开课"],"title":"CS106L: Lec05 Containers","uri":"/2023/01/lec05_containers/#container"},{"categories":["CS106L"],"content":" STL Containers Familiar: vector, stack, queue, set, map Unfamiliar: array : An array is the primitive form of a vector, fixed size in a strict sequence. deque : A deque is a double ended queue. list: A list is a doubly linked list, can loop through in either direction. Two types of containers Sequence: Containers that can be accessed sequentially. Provides access to sequences of elements. Anything with an inherent order goes here. vectors, deques, lists … Associative Containers that don’t necessarily have a sequential order. More easily searched, like maps and sets. maps, sets, unordered maps/sets … VectorAt a high level, a vector is an ordered collection of elements of the any same type that can grow and shrink in size. We keep track of a few member variables size: number of elements in the vector capacity: space allocated for elements // initialization of vector std::vector\u003cint\u003e vec1{3, 5}; // {3, 5} std::vector\u003cint\u003e vec2(3, 5); // {5, 5, 5} // add element vec1.push_back(4); // {3, 5, 4} // get element int a = vec1.at(0); // a = 3 int b = vec1[1]; // b = 5 DequeA deque is a double ended queue, can do everything a vector can do, unlike vector, it is possible and fast to push_front and pop_front. std::deque\u003cint\u003e dq; // add element dq.push_front(2); // {2} dq.push_front(4); // {4, 2} dq.push_back(3); // {4, 2, 3} // delete element dq.pop_front() // {2, 3} dq.pop_back() // {2} 引用 Which to use? vector is the type of sequence that should be used by default, deque is the data structure of choice when most insertions and deletions take place at the beginning or at the end of the sequence. —— C++ ISO Standard ``` Choosing sequence containers MapMaps are implemented with key-value pairs with unique keys, std::pair\u003cconst key, value\u003e Based on ordering property of keys, keys need to be comparable using \u003c operator. Ordered maps/sets require a comparison operator to be deﬁned, keys in sorted order. Unordered maps/sets require a hash function to be deﬁned, keys are unordered. 示例 std::map\u003cint, string\u003e mymap; string str = mymap.at(key); // throw error if the key not exists. str = mymap[key]; // will not throw error if the key not exists. MultimapMultimap is an associative container that contains a sorted list of key-value pairs, while permitting multiple entries with the same key. 示例 std::multimap\u003cint, int\u003e myMMap; myMMap.insert({std::make_pair(3, 3)}); myMMap.insert({3, 12}); cout \u003c\u003c myMMap.count(3) \u003c\u003c endl; // 2 SetSets contains a sorted set of unique objects of type Key. 示例 std::set\u003cstring\u003e myset; // add element myset.insert(\"game\"); // {\"game\"} myset.insert(\"milk\"); // {\"game\", \"milk\"} // check if contains element bool game_exist = myset.count(\"game\"); // true bool hello_exist = myset.count(\"hello\"); // false // remove element myset.earse(\"milk\"); // {\"game\"} ","date":"2023-01-20","objectID":"/2023/01/lec05_containers/:2:1","series":null,"tags":["Cpp","公开课"],"title":"CS106L: Lec05 Containers","uri":"/2023/01/lec05_containers/#stl-containers"},{"categories":["CS106L"],"content":" STL Containers Familiar: vector, stack, queue, set, map Unfamiliar: array : An array is the primitive form of a vector, fixed size in a strict sequence. deque : A deque is a double ended queue. list: A list is a doubly linked list, can loop through in either direction. Two types of containers Sequence: Containers that can be accessed sequentially. Provides access to sequences of elements. Anything with an inherent order goes here. vectors, deques, lists … Associative Containers that don’t necessarily have a sequential order. More easily searched, like maps and sets. maps, sets, unordered maps/sets … VectorAt a high level, a vector is an ordered collection of elements of the any same type that can grow and shrink in size. We keep track of a few member variables size: number of elements in the vector capacity: space allocated for elements // initialization of vector std::vector vec1{3, 5}; // {3, 5} std::vector vec2(3, 5); // {5, 5, 5} // add element vec1.push_back(4); // {3, 5, 4} // get element int a = vec1.at(0); // a = 3 int b = vec1[1]; // b = 5 DequeA deque is a double ended queue, can do everything a vector can do, unlike vector, it is possible and fast to push_front and pop_front. std::deque dq; // add element dq.push_front(2); // {2} dq.push_front(4); // {4, 2} dq.push_back(3); // {4, 2, 3} // delete element dq.pop_front() // {2, 3} dq.pop_back() // {2} 引用 Which to use? vector is the type of sequence that should be used by default, deque is the data structure of choice when most insertions and deletions take place at the beginning or at the end of the sequence. —— C++ ISO Standard ``` Choosing sequence containers MapMaps are implemented with key-value pairs with unique keys, std::pair Based on ordering property of keys, keys need to be comparable using \u003c operator. Ordered maps/sets require a comparison operator to be deﬁned, keys in sorted order. Unordered maps/sets require a hash function to be deﬁned, keys are unordered. 示例 std::map mymap; string str = mymap.at(key); // throw error if the key not exists. str = mymap[key]; // will not throw error if the key not exists. MultimapMultimap is an associative container that contains a sorted list of key-value pairs, while permitting multiple entries with the same key. 示例 std::multimap myMMap; myMMap.insert({std::make_pair(3, 3)}); myMMap.insert({3, 12}); cout \u003c\u003c myMMap.count(3) \u003c\u003c endl; // 2 SetSets contains a sorted set of unique objects of type Key. 示例 std::set myset; // add element myset.insert(\"game\"); // {\"game\"} myset.insert(\"milk\"); // {\"game\", \"milk\"} // check if contains element bool game_exist = myset.count(\"game\"); // true bool hello_exist = myset.count(\"hello\"); // false // remove element myset.earse(\"milk\"); // {\"game\"} ","date":"2023-01-20","objectID":"/2023/01/lec05_containers/:2:1","series":null,"tags":["Cpp","公开课"],"title":"CS106L: Lec05 Containers","uri":"/2023/01/lec05_containers/#vector"},{"categories":["CS106L"],"content":" STL Containers Familiar: vector, stack, queue, set, map Unfamiliar: array : An array is the primitive form of a vector, fixed size in a strict sequence. deque : A deque is a double ended queue. list: A list is a doubly linked list, can loop through in either direction. Two types of containers Sequence: Containers that can be accessed sequentially. Provides access to sequences of elements. Anything with an inherent order goes here. vectors, deques, lists … Associative Containers that don’t necessarily have a sequential order. More easily searched, like maps and sets. maps, sets, unordered maps/sets … VectorAt a high level, a vector is an ordered collection of elements of the any same type that can grow and shrink in size. We keep track of a few member variables size: number of elements in the vector capacity: space allocated for elements // initialization of vector std::vector vec1{3, 5}; // {3, 5} std::vector vec2(3, 5); // {5, 5, 5} // add element vec1.push_back(4); // {3, 5, 4} // get element int a = vec1.at(0); // a = 3 int b = vec1[1]; // b = 5 DequeA deque is a double ended queue, can do everything a vector can do, unlike vector, it is possible and fast to push_front and pop_front. std::deque dq; // add element dq.push_front(2); // {2} dq.push_front(4); // {4, 2} dq.push_back(3); // {4, 2, 3} // delete element dq.pop_front() // {2, 3} dq.pop_back() // {2} 引用 Which to use? vector is the type of sequence that should be used by default, deque is the data structure of choice when most insertions and deletions take place at the beginning or at the end of the sequence. —— C++ ISO Standard ``` Choosing sequence contai